CNN delays segment about Facebook's identity/orientation expansion. Lauren explains why that matters.
seeds.description: I was asked to be on CNN today to talk about Facebook's groundbreaking inclusion of 58 different gender options. As someone who identifies outside the gender binary, Facebook's gender inclusion is one major victory in our long fight. I was really looking forward to bringing this historic achievement to light and mainstream media. Unfortunately, the segment was postponed at the last minute while I was en route to the studio. There are many people all over who were looking forward to my appearance on CNN and to hear what I had to say. Rather than disappoint, I have decided to go ahead and deliver what I would have said on CNN about such an important topic!

The Price of a Life in Rural America: hospital closing threatens lives in Hyde County, NC
seeds.description: http://www.storyofamerica.org/belhaven1 The U.S. Dept. of Justice has offered mediation to Vidant Health and the North Carolina NAACP to resolve a Title 6 complaint under the Civil Rights Act of 1964. Rev. Dr. William Barber, president of the North Carolina NAACP, has travelled to Belhaven, NC three times this year to join in local efforts to prevent the closing of Vidant Pungo Hospital, which was purchased by Vidant Health two years ago. In part 2 of our video series, and, in more detail in the video below, Rev. Barber explains the complaint, citing Title 6 of the Civil Rights Act which prohibits entities that receive federal funds from spending them in ways that discriminate against minorities. Whether intended or not, Vidant's decision to close the Belhaven hospital would have a disproportionate impact on African Americans, thousands of whom have lived in the region since emancipation. Note: this is from a partner so please let Ari know if you write it up - thanks! Note thought: we are note licensing this content.

North Korea: Life in the camps
seeds.description: In this video former prisoners and their captors expose the horror of life inside North Korea's prison camps. They describe forced abortions, impossibly hard labour, starvation and prisoners forced to dig their own graves. Note: I couldn't finish this video it is so horrible. I still think that we should share it bc it is really important. Carly, if you approve this feel free to assign to someone else. Also, if someone writes this up please let me know bc it was sent to me by Amnesty International Australia and I can let them know we're writing it up. CG: WOW yes, this is difficult but very important. A good alternative to those VICE docs in that it's really about the awful realities over there & elevates the awful human rights violations they're experiencing. I set it to unassigned.

The true cost of oil: Garth Lenz @ TEDxVictoria
seeds.description: What does environmental devastation actually look like? At TEDxVictoria, photographer Garth Lenz shares shocking photos of the Alberta Tar Sands mining project -- and the beautiful (and vital) ecosystems under threat. For almost twenty years, Garth's photography of threatened wilderness regions, devastation, and the impacts on indigenous peoples, has appeared in the world's leading publications. His recent images from the boreal region of Canada have helped lead to significant victories and large new protected areas in the Northwest Territories, Quebec, and Ontario. Garth's major touring exhibit on the Tar Sands premiered on Los Angeles in 2011 and recently appeared in New York. Garth is a Fellow of the International League Of Conservation Photographers Permissions would need to come via: http://garthlenz.com/#/contact Note: this was referred to us by a partner so please let Ari know if you write it up. ////CG: Great pictures, & video... Important stuff here!!!

seeds.title: Amanda Tapping (actress on Stargate SG-1) talks about female costumes and the military
seeds.description: Found by Tim Transcript: When I started Stargate, I got the part, I was SO thrilled to have this INCREDIBLE character, to be playing someone in the military. I had SO much respect, to be playing someone who’s so smart and so liberated and… I thought “Yes!” I had to weeks to move from Toronto to Vancouver. I flew out there, I had my first wardrobe fitting. And one of the things that was in… THE thing that was in the wardrobe room was a very low-cut tank-top and a push-up bra… And I turned to the custom designer - whom I’ve worked with since, who’s wonderful - and I said “What… What is this?” And she said “Well.. they wanna see what you look like in it.” And I said “…but this… NOBODY in the military, no captain in the US airforce would wear this… while her male counterparts are wearing crewneck t-shirts and… I c… I can’t do it!” And she said “Well, they just wanna see what you look like and take a picture and…” I was like “…”. And I PANICKED because I thought, I had just been given this AMAZING opportunity - I didn’t know it would last 10 years but I knew it was gonna be a kick-ass show - and I was like… “I can’t do it…” And I started to cry and I said “You have to go upstairs and tell them I’m not doing it. And if it means that they recast the part then recast the part but you’ve cast a smart woman and you’ve cast somebody who has NEVER tried to get a job based on her looks or her body, I’ve always played strong, smart women, I… I can’t do it. So if they wanna recast the part I totally get it but I’m not playing THAT version of this character.” But I’m saying this while I’m blubbering because I’m suffering that I’ve just lost maybe the best job of my career… And so she said “Okay” and I said “I’m sorry, I’m sorry, I’m sorry, I’ve NEVER been difficult, I don’t… but I CAN’T do that!” So she went upstairs and she came back down and she said “Okay, no problem.” And I said “Okay, so what’s my costume?” And she said “Well…” And I said “Just… What are the guys wearing?” So she handed me a black T-Shirt and the BDUs, which is what my character would wear in the field with her male counterparts, and that’s where we went from there. But that to me was the defining moment of… And I STILL cry about it because I still remember that young woman on the verge of breaking into the… new something big, being petrified that she was gonna loose it, but… I knew that I couldn’t play the TNA version of Sam Carter.

seeds.title: What's going on in Venezuela in a nutshell
seeds.description: CG: Here are some fact check things that you may want to include in your write-up: TL;DR: This seems mostly in line with what major media is reporting, but there are a few small things. The Guardian has reported on the video and didn't note any problems. Overall, probably fine — any mistakes don't seem to be intentional. Here are things of note: — She has the name of one of the victims wrong, and it can't be chalked up to a misreported name. She has Bassil Dasilva, but it's Bassil da Costa (or Dacosta in some versions). Plus, no U.S. or U.K. media is reporting Neyder Sierra. The three that are mentioned more often are da Costa, Roberto Redman, and Juan Montoya. This *could* be chalked up to that Montoya was a police officer killed in a group facing off with students where as da Costa, Redman, and Sierra are all students. So it's probably OK and just due to selective reporting on both her part and the media's — though it's interesting she neglects to mention the officer killed. — Which leads to the next point: She mentions the brutality of the government to the students (totally confirmed), but in quite a few reports, student groups are also reported to be lobbing gas bombs and rocks at police and blocking streets with burning trash. — The last thing is that while I could confirm the study she mentions about 25,000 homicides, I didn't find any solid news or academic support for 90% going unpunished. *BUT* there's probably some truth behind it because otherwise Venezuelan prisons would be overflowing. So that I could easily let go as a "generalized" figure.

"Come Together" TV ad -- International HIV/AIDS Alliance - Couples of all kinds having sex to promote safe, consensual sex for all
seeds.description: From links@ - Maybe too much - use your judgement or run it by Carly for another opinion. Charles Rivington charles.rivington@bluefroglondon.com I wanted to suggest that this brand new UK charity Valentine's campaign celebrating safe sex in all its many forms might be Upworthy. (Full disclosure, I was the copywriter on this campaign but I do feel very strongly about the cause and it would meant he world to us if you would feature it on your wonderful website.) Launching with a provocative tv ad, the underlying message of the campaign is that "as long as you experience sex in a consensual, open and safe way, you should be free to explore your sexuality and indulge your sexual desires, even if some parts of society might judge you for them." The joyful ad features both gay and straight couples, threesomes, transgendered men and women and interracial partners of both sexes. The campaign is aimed at getting people to give money to the International HIV/AIDS Alliance that they can use to ensure that people all over the world can have access to safe sex - regardless of their age, race, background, gender, sexual identity or religion. If people give more than £20, they also get the Come Together Box as a thank you, which raunchy items designed to help people celebrate great, safe sex. Here is a link to the provocative advert on YouTube: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fIn3pGrKC5E The campaign microsite: https://www.wecometogether.org Some articles in the press about the campaign: http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/provocative-new-ad-aimed-at-promoting-safe-sex-tells-people-to-come-together-to-fight-aids-9111689.html http://www.thedrum.com/news/2014/02/09/ad-day-international-hivaids-alliance-come-together http://www.nerve.com/love-sex/this-video-showcases-dozens-of-orgasms-to-promote-safer-sex Please let me know if you have any questions or comments.

seeds.title: Edythe Kirchmaier on Super Soul Sunday
How much we waste on food waste (+ videos on how to save)
seeds.description: CG: cool stuff here! Lots more videos in the second URL... perhaps combine? Perhaps separate?? The choice is yours. "The brutal truth of food waste is this. Your home probably spends $1,000 a year on edible food that is never eaten. In the US the average is $900 a year, in the UK it’s £700 and in Australia it’s over $1,000! We don’t waste food on purpose, but somehow between the demands of our busy lives and being bombarded with food on sale we’ve got in the habit of wasting a colossal amount of food. On this page I’m going to share 5 simple habits that have helped our family save food and money. This isn’t some program you need to follow step by step. If you think one of the steps might work for you, start with that one! Read more at http://shrinkthatfootprint.com/how-to-save-money-on-food-waste#9OS4paKZPbFyOgbW.99"

Myth Busters: Throwing Like A Girl
seeds.description: The MythBusters show on The Discovery Channel tackles urban legends and misconceptions of all kinds so they recently decided to debunk a classic sexist insult, “You throw like a girl!” To test the myth that boys and men are better at throwing than girls and women, hosts Adam Savage and Jamie Hyneman evaluated the throws of males and females from four age groups: 7, 12, 18, and 24. In their first test, they determined that girls and women threw more slowly than boys and men, but were often more accurate. To narrow in on potential differences in throwing technique, they took the 7-year-olds and the 24-year-olds to a motion capture laboratory, and found that the girls tended to throw with an upright torso, while boys leaned forward -- a technique that paralleled that used by Greg Reynolds, a professional baseball pitcher who was also filmed using motion capture. However, as Adam points out, “we can’t shake this cultural generality that playing catch, throwing a ball is a boy’s game and not a girl’s game. How do you control for that inherent cultural training?” After putting some thought into the matter, the team came up with an ingenious solution: “we are making all eight of our test subjects throw again... but with their left hand this time.” After all, as the narrator of the show points out, “without practice, it’s impossible to transfer a learned athletic skill to your non-preferred hand, meaning this test effectively cancels out any subtle cultural training that may give the boys an advantage.” The result was conclusive: Adam reported, “when we removed all that training and had our ‘blank slates’ throw with their non-dominant hand, males and females threw with almost identical techniques. This suggests strongly that it is cultural, that it is training and that when you remove that training, you level the playing field.” Of course, it’s always good to verify your results, and to do that, they invited Jordan Taylor, pitcher for the USA National Softball Team, to participate. As the narrator says, “Jordan is a girl... and Jordan can throw her 65 mile per hour cannons and hit the target with unfailing accuracy, and her form matches that of Greg, the male pro pitcher.” The show acknowledges that Greg’s “larger frame does mean greater speed” but that in terms of technique and accuracy, “Jordan’s got it nailed.” Their conclusion? “[G]iven the training, there’s no reason women can’t overcome cultural bias and throw as well as the guys.” Jamie says at the end of the segment, “Maybe now we can put to bed ‘throws like a girl’ as an insult.” In other words: myth busted! You can watch the 4-minute segment where they bust this myth via the link below. If your Mighty Girl is a fan of the throwing-intensive sports of softball and baseball, you'll find our favorite books celebrating female ballplayers in our blog post, "Play Ball Like A Mighty Girl!: Top Picks for Baseball & Softball Lovers," at http://www.amightygirl.com/blog/?p=2697 For stories of both real-life and fictional girls and women confronting gender stereotypes and discrimination, visit our "Gender Discrimination" section at http://www.amightygirl.com/books/social-issues/prejudice-discrimination?cat=69 For toys and gear of all sorts that are perfect for throwing, visit our "Catching & Throwing" outdoor play section at http://www.amightygirl.com/toys/outdoor-play?cat=602 And, if your Mighty Girl is an athlete, you can find girl-empowering t-shirts that show off her love of sports in our "Sports/Hobbies" t-shirt section at http://www.amightygirl.com/clothing?clothing_themes=145

seeds.description: Would really like to write this up. I think this comment from the vimeo page really sums up why I think it's Upworthy: I joined Vimeo just so I could leave a comment and tell you the impact this video had on me! Thank you so much for making it! My husband and I are newly licensed foster parents and are waiting for our first placement. We watched video after video during our training to help us understand what these kids have gone through and not one of them compares to this. This video is what we need to see, we need to hear this little girl's narrative in our heads when we have little ones acting out and know there is a horrible memory or trigger behind the action. I'm having everyone in my family watch this so they can better understand our future children what they may have gone through. Again, thank you so much for making this video! It is amazing!

CG: This is quite interesting! I was leaning 'no' for a while, as it's not the most substantive, but the point at min 2:00 really struck me as something you don't hear about all that often. I would definitely center your framing more around that point -- the idea that being a non-conformist makes you not as successful -- but it's your name for goodness sakes!

seeds.title: The Controversial Mass Text That You Should Absolutely Not Be Mad About
can you get muscles without meat?
seeds.description: I am fact checking this a bit with the creator who sent it to me. CG: Ehhhh.... this feels a bit more like a diet video rather than tied to a systemic problem... I get the idea of making veganism a bit more accessible (like proving people wrong when they say you'll lack protein or whatever if you go vegan) but I'd rather this be a bit more factually based than just one person's bodybuilding experience (feels a bit isolating and unapproachable... like not only is this about an extreme lifestyle but pairing it with ANOTHER extreme lifestyle!). Also feels like it's missing the systemic tie-in... like, why vegan? Is that actually a lifestyle choice for him or just a fun experiment? Why should we care? CG: Actually, thinking about it again: if your framing was really all about disproving that a vegan lifestyle is weak, then I'd say go for it. I think this one really depends on a strong frame, but I could see it. I set it back to approved... just be mindful of that, or fear more followup haha.

seeds.title: VIDEO: Hari Kondabalu on Female Presidents
A man talks about the need for a draft
seeds.description: I REALLY want to write this one up :) Erin sent it to me. It's about how the fact that we have an all-volunteer military has made us removed from the true cost of war and the best thing we could do to prevent further war would be a draft. CG: WOW, this is really a controversial idea. (Also that he begins with a quote from McChrystal only solidifies that.) Although the idea here is really interesting -- as is the overwhelming problem that we are so very far removed from the realities faced by our military -- I don't think this video in particular communicates it effectively. Fighting a militaristic society (wouldn't an ideal world not need war?) with more militarism (and REQUIRED militarism, at that) doesn't come across as the most "Upworthy" of solutions. A call for more empathy and accountability through the treatment of veterans feels like a more holistic compromise -- but I understand the point here that it's not working. If you'd like to discuss this one further, please let me know as this is a very interesting and unique discussion. I have not heard this argument before. ARI: Here's why: The true cost of war is something that matters - it absolutely is an important issue. The option presented here is definitely a controversial one - and not one that I even fully agree with - but one that makes you really think "would I be in favor of this war if it was my wife, my daughter, etc. going on the front lines?" Do I think we would have invaded Iraq or Afghanistan if the Bush daughters were on the front lines? Absolutely not. The approach, though, is not that far fetched. We've done it before and Israel uses this approach - everyone must participate in the military - and I'm not saying that it works or is a good idea, but I have to believe that any country would engage in less aggressive behavior knowing that all of its people have skin in the choices made, not just some. My idea is actually 2 yrs of required service for all at age 18 - civil or int'l (I would like to get rid of the word military/defense altogether and combine state dept and USAID activities with military so they are not so disjointed and have them be more coordinated) and I would want to discuss that (super briefly) in the lede. There are a lot of assumptions about people in the military that this tackles: Many people I know who are in the military do not believe in either war in Iraq or Afghanistan - why did they join the military then? They want a peaceful world and want to help stand up for human rights worldwide to help achieve that. The military participates in lots of peacekeeping missions with the UN and goes to any emergency mission to coordinate aid. People in the military aren't necessarily war-mongers - many want to participate in int'l relations in-person not just through papers. That said, there are also a lot of people in the military who really didn't choose it - they are there bc they grew up poor, or in the system (foster care, etc.), and saw this as a stable option. As long as you have a clean record, you can arrive at boot camp with literally nothing but the skin on your body. They will even give you underwear. So if you are poor and see no options, the military is something that seems like a secure and organized opportunity that rewards hard work and not people who grew up with money. In my personal opinion, overall I think Upworthy needs more of this kind of content. I agree that gay rights and body image issues are important (I have written about them, and they are something I deal with daily myself), but I think we could also use dabbling in some more controversial things to show that we are not just going to focus on those things that most people agree with anyway, and we can do so in a way that is Upworthy. CG: Approved!!!

seeds.title: Paralympian Snowboarder Amy Purdy
seeds.description: Earlier this week, ABC made the cast announcement for the 18th season of "Dancing With the Stars.” One of the stars that will be dancing this season is Paralympian Snowboarder Amy Purdy. She is the first double amputee to participate on the show, and she is currently in Sochi, where she will be competing in Para-Snowboarding on March 14th. In addition to her participation on the show, Duracell is thrilled to welcome Amy as another #TrustYourPower brand ambassador, joining the ranks of Super Bowl champion Derrick Coleman and the 49ers' Patrick Willis. Amy's incredible story is featured in a new video from Duracell, available via: http://youtu.be/sD5NDlV8x1U, and launched in conjunction with her DWTS announcement. We hope that you will consider sharing this inspiring story. Please let me know if you have any questions or if there's any other information I could provide.

From links@: Jordan Simpson <jsimpson10593@yahoo.com> Hi, My name is Jordan Simpson, the Tedx Curators pushed for me to recommend my performance with you guys so here's the Link!! I hope you find this video worth posting!! http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zj48UMdFKkg This is Meta Four Houston's Jordan Simpson (Me), Tiffany Ike, and Daniel Ortiz Performing our Poem Called "Fire Starters". This poem is a social critique on our generation emphasizing the fact that our generation is lacking the "spark" of innovation. We tend to have all the technological advancements we think we need to not want to advance any further. We are encouraging our peers to keep the "flame" alive by continuing to create.

seeds.title: Schoolgirls put message to end FGM into song
seeds.description: A rather uplifting video from a bunch of school girls calling on an end to female genital mutilation. Would be cool to link this to a nugget w/ more background on FGM (e.g. https://farm.upworthy.com/seeds/531624f381101ef0ea00002d), since people may share something like this more than they would a super depressing video on what FGM actually is. CG: Definitely like where your head is at with adding more context! Be sure to include all the hashtag info and such.

seeds.title: CCA: The Biggest Prison Profiteer Of Them All
seeds.description: From links@: Caitlin Graf <caitlin@thenation.com> *needs fact check We've also just posted the latest video in a special series from The Nation created in partnership with Beyond Bars, a project of Brave New Foundation, and the ACLU: meet the company that wants you in prison: http://www.thenation.com/article/176997/video-why-company-wants-you-prison The Corrections Corporation of America made $1.7 billion last year locking people up. If the SAFE Act passes, they could make even more. I hope this is something you'll consider sharing with your amazing network, and will plan on being touch with future projects down the road. Thanks for considering, Caitlin Tana fact checked on Nov. 11 - Laura
